<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">As the verb phrase of the resolution is the only line separating affirming from negating, we look here to derive round burdens.</span></span>
<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Because, in “ought not possess”, “ought” is the assisting verb while “not possessing” is the main predicate, the affirmative burden is to prove that:</span></span>
<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">It is desirable for states to NOT possess nuclear weapons.</span></span>
<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">The negative, meanwhile, must advocate that this is not true</span></span>
<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">—that it is not desirable for states to NOT, or refrain from the choice to, possess nuclear weapons. </span></span>

<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">**o/**</span></span>
<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Observations:</span></span>
<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Because the actor of the resolution is stated as plural—ie. “states”, the affirmative must advocate that states ought generally not possess. Advocating that a specific state or group states ought not possess is not sufficient to affirm.</span></span>
<span style="font: 12.0px Times New Roman; margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Because the status quo is that nuclear weapons are in use in some but not all nations, the affirmative must advocate that states ought not possess nuclear weapons, even in the current occurrence of other states possessing them.</span></span>

